Endangered onion: three cheetah cubs born in Iran
The world's fastest animal falls victim to brutal hunting, droughts and fatal road accidents across the Islamic Republic
As a result, their number dropped to less than 20 cheetahs.
Three Asian cheetah cubs recently emerged into the world in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
It is a rare birth, which only slightly improves the tragic condition of the endangered animal in the country due to droughts, hunters and fatal road accidents.
This is the first birth of a captive cheetah in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in the wild.
The Iranian news agency IRNA reported that the veterinary team, which is responsible for the Turan National Park in northern Samnan Province, had decided on an imperial birth in captivity.
It has also been noted that fewer than 20 cheetahs have recently been recorded in seven different counties in the country.
Due to the danger of their extinction, the United Nations implemented a defence plan for them as early as 2001.
Now, in Iran, it is hoped that the new cubs will be able to bring about an increase in the population of cheetahs in the future.
In January, Iran's deputy minister for environmental affairs, Hassan Akbari, said that the population of cheetahs in the country had decreased dramatically from 100 cheetahs in 2010 to just 12 cheetahs.
"Their situation is extremely serious," Akbari said, noting that the cheetahs fell victim to drought in their habitats, hunting and even road accidents.
The cheetah is considered to be the fastest animal in the world capable of reaching speeds of about 100 km/h.
The cheetahs can be found in various locations across the globe, from India to Senegal in West Africa.
Spotify Wants to Upgrade Your Car: We Tested the Car Thing
Quietly, Spotify began to try its luck in the hardware world as well.
After years of development - Car Thing was unveiled and launched as a small experiment in the US
We put a hand on the first device in Israel
The Vision: Make Your Old Cars Smart
The Car Thing is Spotify's first hardware product, and was built specifically to provide a solution for people with old cars.
A few weeks ago, I was given an initial opportunity to try the new product, which is currently only available to individual experimenters in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the delivery timing was outstanding, as our home vehicle broke down and we had to drive for a few days with an old system replacement.
After two weeks of playing around, I realized how the Car Thing could easily become an integral part of many people's system.
On the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty about a global launch, I believe many would already prefer to use other solutions.
From idea to reality
Somewhere in 2018, Spotify users began getting an interesting offer in their email box – an option to purchase a new device with voice control and fourth generation connectivity, which would make any old car system smart.
The rumors slowly faded until a year later, when the Financial Times website revealed that the company plans to soon introduce a new product to a vehicle simulating a smart radio with Bluetooth connectivity.
A few months later, these rumors returned to the headlines again after the music service updated with the vehicle status – the same one we know today from the app – triggered as soon as the smartphone detects a connection to the system in the car.
Two years have passed since then.
After countless rumors and leaks, Spotify unveiled Car Thing in April, its smart car system.
Spotify has chosen to release the new device in a very limited way, with a long waiting list and many delays when it comes to shipping.
So of course, right after the press conference that she held, I went on the website and signed up.
Two months later, the long-awaited message arrived.
Reconnecting to the site will buy me the option to purchase the device with a little surprise - it will cost me nothing.
After another month of waiting, the messenger finally knocked on my door, accompanied by a small box with Spotify's logo on it.
The Car Thing
First and foremost, Spotify's device impressed me greatly with the quality of its construction.
And it's a little smaller than my iPhone 11 and features a big, bright, sharp touchscreen in front of it than I expected.
Also, you can find alongside the screen a round and dial button that you can rotate to navigate between the interface screens.
And despite the huge dial, which you can see in the pictures, the Car Thing manages to maintain a relatively thin profile and not stand out too much from the dashboard.
Personally, I would prefer that the company allow changing the dial activity so that I can control the volume of the smartphone, as I can navigate through the touch screen as well.
It may be possible to update a future version.
The device comes in a small, minimalist cardboard box, which includes, among other things, a USB Type C cable and various adapters for its installation.
Many of you probably remember how in the past we used to disconnect the radios and hide them in a drawer after exiting the vehicle.
Car Thing definitely brings that feeling back with its construction form.
All adapters connected to the body of the device using a magnet that was very strong, which prevented it from falling even when traveling on dirt roads.
In addition, throughout the whole top you can find small buttons, which can be easily set up to run various playlists or podcasts.
By long clicking on one of the buttons while listening, or by asking the voice assistant, I have set up some playlists that I hear frequently and the radio show that I listen to every morning on the road.
In doing so, the feature made me feel that the Car Thing is more like a car radio than an extension of my smartphone.
An old car for a smart car.
After a fairly simple physical setup, I connected the Car Thing to the electricity.
I was pleasantly surprised by the setup process.
The instructions were clear, the connection to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later I reached the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone via Bluetooth and controls the app like a remote control, so it can copy all the information on our account from it.
This means that you will still have to connect your smartphone to the vehicle, whether through Bluetooth or through AUX cable in order to hear the music.
The home screen is familiar to all users of the app, since like the app on a smartphone, it places emphasis on album images and playlists.
Also, on the home screen, like the one on the app, you can find recommendations for music depending on your taste, the search screen, and your personal library.
As mentioned above, you can navigate between the different screens using the touchscreen or the manual handheld.
Furthermore, you can at any time call the device's voice assistant by saying "Hey Spotify".
Through it, you can run songs, playlists, albums and even search for podcasts.
Manisoni she easily recognized my voice even when the music was playing in the background and the air conditioner blew directly on the device.
This is probably due to the four microphones installed at the top.
It is important to note that at the moment the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the time of publication of the article, there is no information on when such an update will arrive.
Is it worth waiting for him?
My experience of using the device was great, which is a positive surprise to me given that it is still in the initial release stage.
Also used intensively on long trips, the device continued to work smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
Nevertheless, a small stuttering has occasionally been recorded at the interface, but I believe Spotify will handle such bugs with future version updates.
It is evident that the Swedish company has worked on it a lot in recent years, and of the various versions leaked online during this period, the design of the final product is probably my favorite.
Still, when I first saw the Car Thing, I wondered who exactly the company was trying to target.
After all, his activity boils down to controlling the app on a smartphone, and not much more.
What is different from buying a car with a few shekels and connecting it so that the smartphone is closer to us when driving?
This question is reinforced when considering that iPhone and Android devices are much more powerful than Spotify, and will often buy the user much more functionality.
Despite all this, as I used Car Thing more and more, I understood how it could improve the driving experience.
Being able to see the Waze on my smartphone and control the music on a completely different screen is one I have come to appreciate in the last two weeks.
One question remains – will Spotify even launch the device to the general public?
And if so, will it also be launched here in our small country?
The Swedish company isn't telling much right now.
She has not even shared how many test subjects she currently operates around the world, and how much she plans to add in the limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for sure is the price that is expected to be $79 (about NIS 255).
Meanwhile, the Car Thing provides a first glimpse of the concept Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
Spotify Israel said that there is currently no information on a plan to launch the device in the country
(Laughs)
Have you recruited Talent for the company?
This way you will keep the competitors from "taking" it for you.
The economy is still in a labor market largely dominated by workers, and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talent
Here are some tips to help you keep it in the workplace.
(Laughs)
Despite the increase recorded in the past month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be among the lowest in the world, and in the top ten among OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5 percent (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics).
That is, the economy is still in a labor market that is largely controlled by the workers and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable workers – the talent.
When it comes to those professionals and managers who are focal points of proven knowledge, experience and competence – the trends in the labor market show that the competition for them, the talent as they are referred to by employers, still exists at full strength.
This means that in the current job market situation they do not have the luxury of resting on the laurels even a minute after the recruitment of a desirable Talent, as once he enters the company's doors another company will try to kidnap him to it.
In other words, the competition for talent is so fierce that even after their recruitment they will continue to receive a plethora of tempting job offers, with 30% of employees leaving just a month from getting the job and starting the job.
That is why intelligent employers will move immediately from the stage of recruiting the talent to its conservation stage, with the path starting first and foremost with preparation and creativity already in the process of absorbing it.
An efficient, structured and thoughtful absorption process will make the talent excited about its new place of work from day one and even look forward to the coming.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper absorption process that will help in the preservation of the new talent:
It's no secret - sharing and readiness of the organization
Share the factors that will work with him on his recruitment, explaining why he is vital and important to society and the role, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who comes to where he is expected and understands his worth will feel welcome and will strive to prove the expectations that a son is hanging.
Knowledge is Power – Coordinating Expectations
As early as the first day, the Talent had a meeting of expectations.
Get to know his professional background and see where he sees himself in the future, so you can show him the diverse and unique tools you and the workplace can provide to get there.
We are all people – personal acquaintances
During the days of absorption, try to get to know the talent beyond its professional qualities and take an interest in its hobbies and interests.
A new employee who shows interest in him and allows him to realize and express himself beyond the limits of his position will appreciate it and would like to keep it.
Curiosity precedes
Already in the absorption stage you can create an attractiveness that will make the talent want to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily by discussing bonuses and benefits, but by exposing it to an exciting field or interesting technology, as such stimuli to creativity lead to curiosity and increased interest in the workplace.
The talent was also encouraged to voice his thoughts and opinions to the various projects in the company and made it clear that they were important to the organization.
The writer is the CEO of Manpower Israel – the largest placement and personnel company in Israel.
Electrocution in the pocket: the cost of not closing the coal stations in June - NIS 1 billion
Report of the Knesset Research and Information Center: Failure to close the coal stations at a date set in June 2022 is estimated to be approximately NIS 1 billion
Electric Corporation: "The policy of the use of fuels is first and foremost dictated by the Ministry of Energy"
(Laughs)
The economic cost due to the failure to close the coal stations at the date set in June 2022 is estimated at approximately NIS 1 billion for 2022, a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center reveals.
According to the report, this cost is reflected in the consumer electricity tariff, which is expected to rise in the coming months because of the coal price increase.
In addition, by 2023, an additional excess amount of coal use of about 900,000 tons is expected, so this will be reflected in an additional cost to the electricity economy for not closing the coal stations, assuming that the price of natural gas will remain significantly lower relative to the price of coal.
The report said that the reduction of about one billion shekels in the electricity tariff in 2022 meant a reduction of about 4% in the electricity consumption rate for the home consumer.
That is, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about a billion shekels, and the total discount that could have been to the home consumer is about 4%.
It should be noted that in the framework of the reform in the electricity economy, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary of the Electric Corporation, which would establish units operated by natural gas, intended to replace the hydrocarbon units 4-1 on the site of the Rabin lights.
Following this decision, a government decision was made in July 2018, stating that the operations of the coal-fired production units should be stopped 4-1 at the Orot Rabin power plant.
The decision set schedules, so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly the 4-1 carbon production units will also cease to operate at that time.
The electricity company said in response: "The policy of the use of fuels is first and foremost dictated by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the ministry's decisions, a policy has been implemented in Israel for several years to reduce the use of coal to a minimum possible even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas."
Paying the Price: Everything you need to know for the interest rate increase
Incessant Cuts: Next week the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percent
How much will the mortgage charge be?
What is recommended to do?
All answers
The worsening inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of more than 4% in the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise interest rates on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts estimate an increase rate that ranges from 0.25 to 0.5 percent.
If interest rates rise by half a percent, it will already be 1.25%, the highest level in nine years.
That is, after years of interest in the economy was close to zero.
The sharp increase in interest rates makes mortgage repayments drastically more expensive and burdens households.
With the help of Shai Zertz, a mortgage specialist, we checked how much more we would pay and what we would recommend doing right now.
If interest rates rise by half a percent – how much will the monthly mortgage payment cost?
In a mortgage amounting to NIS 1.2 million, consisting of 40% prime interest rate track, the monthly repayment will increase by NIS 125.
How much has the average mortgage increased since the beginning of the year?
From the beginning of the year, this is a significantly sharper increase.
This is because the interest rates in the rest of the tracks that make up a mortgage (and not just in a prime track) have also increased – in a index-linked track and in the fixed interest track.
If the interest rate does rise by half a percent, the increase will amount to, according to Shazar's estimate, about NIS 620 in a mortgage of approximately NIS 1.2 million.
The Prime route (40% on this route) will complete a cost increase of approximately NIS 280, assuming there will be another 0.5% increase next month.
The variable interest rate track is closely indexed (26.7% in this track) will complement the increase of approximately NIS 120.
The fixed interest rate track – not indexed (33.3% on this track) will be increased by 220 shekels.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have a mortgage that is mostly indexed, a bundle recommends considering recycling to non-linked routes.
Mortgage creditors whose monthly repayments have been significantly increased and find it difficult to meet repayments - he recommends that they examine to refinance a mortgage and redeploy it for a longer period.
This is to reduce payments despite rising interest rates, as it is always better to meet repayments rather than to be insolvent.
Regarding new mortgage takers - he strongly recommends getting to know the different routes and adjusting the mortgage to their financial capabilities.
So too in the future when interest rates go down they will be able to make a mortgage refinancing with minimum early repayment fees.
Regarding the purchasers of apartments from a contractor - a bundle recommends that payments be preceded for the contractor and take a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the "construction input index" increases the price of the property significantly even after the purchase contract has been signed.
The Housing Input Price Index has increased 6.6% in the past year.
Against the background of the increase in this index, on Monday the Banking Supervision Department announced that it was considering creating a mechanism that would allow to include the adherence within the mortgages, but the final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
Fuel prices are rising – and Israelis will be forced to pay more than NIS 8 per litre in July.
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price per liter of 95 octane gasoline, will be NIS 8.08
At the same time, it will be extended to the end of 2022, the reduction of half a shekel per litre in tax on the diesel
A decade's record: The price of gasoline will jump by 36 cents per litre - and will stand from July 1 at more than NIS 8 per litre.
The new price per liter of 95 octane gasoline will be 8.08 and those wishing to enjoy full service will be required to pay an additional 21 cents per liter.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per litre in the diesel tax will be extended by the end of 2022, the Tax Authority said.
As stated, the price increase is due to the continued increase in oil prices, against the background of the war between Russia and Ukraine and the rise in the dollar rate.
Had it not been for the assumption of half a shekel subsidized by the government since April, the price of fuel would have exceeded the all-time high of NIS 8.25 per litre.
The discount expires at the end of July and the Tax Authority and Treasury are currently promoting publication to public comments of an order extending the reduction in tax on gasoline, which stands at half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
Also, starting August 10, an additional reduction of another half-shekel will be determined, so that only from this date will the price of a liter of gasoline be reduced by one shekel by November 15, 2022.
This was reported by the Tax Authority.
"We've reached a situation where I can't remember five months in a row of state income surpluses.
We started a few months ago with the issue of tax reduction on the diesel.
We've been working on an extension for another four months of the Bello, Gasoline and Solar tax - instead of a half-shekel per shekel.
It's good for the industry and the citizenry.
If we lower, it will affect inflation, reduce production, and ease the cost of living.
As Minister of Finance, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus first of all on this," Lieberman said at the Hurwitz Conference on Economics and Society of the Israel Democracy Institute.
As of today, more than half of the price of fuel is the taxes that the government charges (the Blue Tax and VAT) – and this is a high tax rate compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic impact on the cost of living in the economy - because it affects both household and business expenses, public transport and airfare prices, transportation costs, and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the most friendly city for businesses
Open Hope came second in the Ministry of Economy's Business Doing Rankings
Followed by: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon LeZion
Minister Barbbayi: "Corona stressed the importance of local government in the development of business"
(Laughs)
Ashdod is the most friendly city for small and medium businesses.
For the third year in a row, the Small and Medium Business Agency's Doing Business Index found that the Ministry of Economy and Industry ranked local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petach Tikva and in third place streets.
Next are located in order: Ashkelon, Rishon LeZion, Tel Aviv-Jaffa, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Beersheba, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency conducts the Local Authorities Index.
This is the fifth time and its purpose is to serve as a tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance to other authorities in a variety of parameters, as well as to analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The measure is based on several parameters that are examined in each authority, which examine the level of the "friendlyness" of the Authority for Business in its field.
The measure divides the authorities into three groups of magnitude according to the number of residents, since a local authority of up to 50,000 inhabitants is not similar to a local authority of more than 150,000 inhabitants.
T.C. jumped this year.
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different ratings in each local authority: business satisfaction, tender accessibility, information accessibility, and arnona.
The ranking shows that Ramat Gan dropped from second place to eighth place, Bat Yam dropped from fourth place to twelfth place and Netanya dropped from fifth place to thirteenth place.
A decline in ranking does not mean that the Authority's business service has deteriorated, and in many cases it is due to the fact that the service of other business authorities has improved and they have increased in rankings, while the Authority's declining rankings have less improved its services to business.
Among the immigrants in the ranking are Petach Tikva, which rose from 6th to 2nd, and streets that rose from 12th to 3rd.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from 4th to 11th in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to 6th.
"Business - Growth Engine"
The ranking shows that the Galilee landscape leads in local authorities that include between 50,000 and 150,000 residents.
It is followed by Kiryat Motzkin, Mateh Binyamin, Modiin-Maccabim-Reut, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod HaSharon.
In 28th and last place is Tiberias.
"The index is intended to encourage local authorities to facilitate small and medium-sized businesses, starting from the time the business opened and throughout its activities with the authorities," says Minister of Economy and Industry Orna Barbbay.
"Businesses constitute a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for about 50% of the business product and about 60% of the employees in the economy.
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct influence on the businesses that are in it.
The corona emphasized the importance of local government and we saw that authorities who acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them became the first government interface for them."
Ran Kuti, director of the Small and Medium Business Agency at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: "Local authorities have a central and fundamental part in the ability of businesses in their fields to thrive and flourish.
In the past two years, in which we are dealing with the Corona crisis, authorities have greater weight in helping businesses survive in their fields and survive at all."
2021 by mail: 20 parcels per household - and a leap in weight
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 – similar to 2020
Average weight per pack stands at 435 grams - a jump of 36% compared to 2020
The busiest month: December, when the average package weight stood at 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail parcels arrived in Israel, on average almost 20 packages per household, according to Israel Post data obtained by Israel Today.
The number of packages reached in 2021 is similar to 2020, which reached 46.5 million packages in Israel, and lower than 2019 – which reached 61.6 million packages.
This year, however, there has been a jump of more than 36% in the weight of packages coming from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products arrived in Israel from abroad, a 36% increase from 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in Consumption Habits
The average weight per pack jumped 60 percent in two years – from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The jump in package weight is mainly influenced by two major trends, both from the seller and from the buyer: the major overseas shopping sites combine items for one shipment and no longer ship each product from the "shopping basket" in a separate package.
On the part of the Israeli consumer, the rapid delivery of the shipments, within a few days of the order, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which the purchasers are interested in receiving close to making the purchase.
Also in 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month when the most packages came from abroad at the highest weight and the highest number of items is December, with 4.2 million packages weighing a total of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per pack was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
The Black Friday Effect
More packages arrived in December than any other month, possibly following the November shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles Day, Black Friday and Cyber Monday.
The large orders begin to arrive in Israel between one and two weeks after the purchase.
Study: Most employees in the economy are unaware that tax returns can be obtained
Many employees deserve money from the state, which can reach tens of thousands of shekels
Have you changed jobs?
Did you go out to the U.S.A.?
Have you moved from town to town?
You may be entitled to receive a substantial sum in a simple procedure
All the details – inside.
Most renters are unaware of the fact that they are entitled to tax returns, which can accrue to high amounts.
The State Comptroller noted in a report from about two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds of NIS 3.6 billion, which means that you should also check whether you are eligible to receive tax refunds.
Many employees can receive a high amount, as four out of five employees are eligible for tax refunds.
In practice, however, tens of thousands of employees are served each year.
If you think these funds are going to go to waste anyway, think again: Hirers can apply for income tax refunds for six years back.
Tax:On conducted an in-depth study of 4,000 of its customers regarding tax returns during 2020.
The company has over 30,000 customers, so the sample reflects their dispersion in terms of population groups and gender, age and geography.
The data show that during 2020, due to the outbreak of the coronavirus crisis and the expenditure of hundreds of thousands of workers per ILO, there were a number of significant changes, centered on an increase of 15% in the average amount of return to a household that stood at NIS 4,300 per year.
The reason is that the start-up fees are lower than the salaries and therefore there is a gap between what the employee paid as a tax and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest return received in 2020 by a customer of the company was NIS 121,054 for returns over the past 6 years.
What can I get tax returns for?
One of the reasons for receiving tax returns is a change in the workplace.
For the 81% of people who changed jobs during the year, an average tax return of NIS 2,943 was generated.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The figures show that 74% of women who gave birth and spent more than 16 weeks on maternity leave were eligible for an average return of NIS 3,538 for the same year.
Another reason for the return is donations.
100% of the people who donate and pay taxes have been refunded.
Another reason for the refund is non-registration credits for alimony. 63%
From the divorced we have not updated a credit point for alimony and therefore the tax refund for any year that has not been updated such a credit point is NIS 2,616.
Due to unemployment - Expenditure to the IHL: 93% of those who were sick or unemployed and who earned over 12,000 shekels received a tax return of NIS 4021 for the same year.
Other reasons for tax refunds are: reimbursement for life insurance payments, life insurance on a mortgage, return on a winning return, return on securities losses, non-registration of credit points for a man for birth and distribution of tax refunds by geographic location.
- 94% of people who deposited personal life insurance or for taking out a mortgage were eligible for a tax refund.
In an examination conducted for every one million shekels from a 25-year mortgage, the cumulative tax return for the period is over 20,000 shekels for the entire period of the mortgage.
100% of those who move to a winning settlement received a tax refund for the transition year since approval of residency in a winning settlement is granted only after 12 months from the date the resident becomes a qualifying resident and thus in fact the first year is paid full tax.
79% of customers holding securities were entitled to a refund of the said years tax.
However, those who hold securities are important to check each year since losses are not rolled out from year to year but only through filing a report.
56% of men who have a child do not register credit points in the year of birth in the pay slip.
The rate of return can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that exists mainly in the Arab sector.
Tax:on CEO, Tal Carmon: "The Corona crisis has caused the Israeli hiring public to become much more active.
He is interested, checks and demands what he deserves in income tax returns.
It turns out that sitting at home, in the IDF or after being fired, of hundreds of thousands of Israelis over long months, has caused many salaried workers to examine in depth what they deserve from the state.
It is important to know that today all procedures for receiving tax returns can be carried out digitally, easily and simply, without the bureaucracy that has deterred many in the past."
Employment Market: Fewer Job Candidates, More Salary
OLJOBS report to conclude 2021: top demand - jobs with no experience
The scope of jobs offered increased by 50%
"Looking for work, but not storming the market"
In the year just ended, there was a 15% drop in the number of resumes sent, and on average only 23 candidates ran for each position, compared to 41 candidates in the previous year, according to a report by the Oljubs website for 2021, on the coronavirus crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were primarily interested in jobs-saturated areas such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, the inexperienced jobs led to the top of the demand with more than 38,000 searches – probably following the return of young people with no professional experience in the search for immediate work, at the end of the VAT payments.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35,000 and 32,000 (respectively), drivers and couriers had 11,000 searches, and retention had little less than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the coronavirus crisis, wages in 2021 rose by 2% compared to 2020, and the average wage in Israel was NIS 11,675 gross.
The monthly salary in the field of software was NIS 17,915 on average, and in information systems analysis it was NIS 17,140.
However, between the center and the periphery there was a wage gap of more than 2,000 shekels: in the center of the country it was 12,500 shekels on average, compared with 10,795 in the north and 10,135 shekels in the south.
Gender-wise, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by the type of work and the extent of the hours, was maintained and stood at 36%.
Men earned NIS 13,295, compared to women's wages of NIS 9,740.
Trying to get back on track.
On the side of business, cross-growth was recorded in almost all branches of the economy, and businesses longed for working hands.
Thus, the supply of jobs increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40,000 jobs at AllJobs.
A survey conducted by the website among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of them indicated their intention to increase the total fundraising but 72% understood that this year would be difficult.
The largest supply was for inexperienced jobsand those were more than 58,000 at the site.
They were followed by customer service and administration roles with about 44,000 jobs in each field, sales and software with 41,000 jobs each, teaching and education with 24,000 vacancies, and stockers still in demand at 19,000 vacancies.
Einav Boymfeld, Director of Research and Content at Oljavos: "The job seekers are trying to get back on track but are not storming the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive jobs in their eyes.
Also, the prolonged disconnection from the work cycle makes it difficult for them to return, and some have found creative ways to make a living."
CBS: Israel's unemployment rate has risen to 6.3%
According to the Bureau survey data, about 270,000 Israelis were left out of work in December 2021.
In November, there were 262,000 unemployed.
The percentage of unemployed people in the first half of December 2021 was 6.3%, about 270,000 Israelis, compared with 6.1% in the second half of November 2021 (about 262,000).
This is according to the Personnel Survey data for the first half of December 2021 of the Central Bureau of Statistics.
The percentage of unemployed was 4.5% in the first half of December 2021 versus 4.3% in the second half of November 2021.
In other words, it's 193 thousand unemployables versus 180.3 thousand.
According to the characteristics of the labor force in the first half of December 2021 among those aged 15 and over, this population included 6,607,500 residents in Israel, excluding institutions and residents outside the settlements.
Of these, 64.4%, i.e. 4,252,700 are in the workforce and the rest, which is 2,354,800, are not in the workforce.
Of those in the workforce 95.5% who make up 4,059,700 are employed and the rest are unemployed.
Of those not in the workforce, 2.3% stopped working because of layoffs or job closures from March 2020.
The Personnel Survey provides information about the workforce in Israel and is regularly conducted by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
In the first half of December 2021, approximately 8,700 people aged 15 and over were regularly interviewed.
In the second half of November 2021, approximately 8,900 people aged 15 and over were regularly interviewed.
The survey population includes the permanent residents of the State of Israel, tourists and temporary residents who have been staying in Israel for more than a year in a row.
The survey enables monitoring of the development in the workforce, its size and features, the extent of unemployment, and more.
"Unobvious": Subliminal sanctifies the Sabbath - and prepares for independence
Celebrating the fact that "we can live the way we want", excited about the audience meeting and making sure to spend time with the children
Weekend and Kobi Shimoni's Independence Day, Subliminal
What does your typical Friday look like?
"Weekends are the most important moments in life for me.
The sanctification and tradition are very deep roots in my soul.
My Fridays are dedicated to children, Or (10) and Jonathan (8).
I pick them up from school, we buy flowers and groceries for consecration, have lunch and do something fun together, like play soccer, ride horses or play cars on a sign.
Sometimes you go to the beach, or even just wash the car, but always stop on the way to buy a gift at the neighborhood toy store – and there is always another excuse.
When we come home with the gifts, the smells of cooking greet us."
What does your Friday meal look like?
"I was blessed with breweries around me.
On my side is a Persian-Tunisai kitchen, full of salads and an atmosphere of laughter, music, singing and joy.
On the side of my wife Ines, who is also a great cook, come the Ukrainian dishes, which are deep and spicy, with lots of meat.
When we get to my mother-in-law, already from the lobby of the building, amazing smells arise from her apartment.
I usually do the sanctification, along with the children, who know him by heart.
In the end, my after-dinner fun is passing out on the carpet, and having the kids jump at me like I'm some kind of inflatable."
Do you have a special childhood memory from the weekends?
"As a child, I would wake up on Saturday to Israeli music on the third network and to the pale tracker skits, which we knew by heart.
My father loved nature and we traveled a lot in the Land of Israel, usually to the north.
Every corner of the country made him proud.
He died three months ago of a serious illness, and for him consecration and Sabbath was the Holy of Holies, mainly in the sense that the whole family should be together.
I recently released a song in his memory called 'Guardian of You', which I created with Osher Cohen.
I believe he was proud of this piece, which sanctifies the bond between father and son."
Soon we will mark the 74th Independence Day. As a zealous Zionist, what are your feelings about the holiday?
Independence Day is a holy day for me, and part of my meaning and identity.
In Persia and Tunisia, my parents had to hide their Jewish identity, while I am an Israeli Jew who gets to live with his children in our country.
A week or two before Independence Day, I would have climbed trees and tied to a string house with Israeli flags.
Today my days of independence are full of performances, and you always meet an insanely happy audience, which celebrates that we can live the way we want.
We need to keep that our children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren have that option as well, and remember that nothing here is self-evident."
Friday: Esty Zakheim welcomes the Sabbath
"My dream is to open a big table and invite all my dead loved ones": a Friday meal that Esty Zakheim dreams of, and how does she deal with the fact that her husband keeps Shabbat?
Tell us about your preparations to sit down.
(Laughs)
"Preparations start as early as Thursday night, when I come back from a play or workshop and cook until three in the morning everything that requires long cooking like a skier, roast and sauces.
On Friday, in the first part of the day, I devote time to myself, meeting with friends and friends for coffee, a play or a movie, or I participate in rehearsals.
In the summer the Sabbaths come in late, and I have plenty of time to sit in the neighborhood garden and watch the sunset or just a good series.
At the Shabbat meal I usually host my mother, Varda, who celebrated 89th, and also friends."
Can you share more cooking?
"I like shortcuts.
For example, instead of peeling 10 onions, cutting and crying, I buy a bag of frozen onions and fry it.
On my Shabbat table you can find meat dishes, vegan tofu dishes, potatoes and cauliflower in the oven.
Most of the cooking I make, and they of course heat up on the plate on Saturday.
Alejandro, my partner, makes chicken soup, vegetable salad and in the winter - the cholent."
Your husband is a religious man and you are from a secular household.
How does it work?
"Living with a Sabbath keeper is an endless compromise.
"And you shall love your neighbor as yourself," in fact.
For family trips he couldn't go out, so I often found myself packing up the kids and joining friends' family trips.
In addition, I am also the children's on-call leader, the one who brings them back Friday night from parties and gatherings.
On the other hand, I also enjoy the benefits of his Shabbat, because I usually don't perform on the Sabbath and get a kind of 'forced vacation' - and that's a good thing."
Who would you like to host on Saturday?
"I would open a big table and invite'my dead'.
Sometimes I imagine what it would have been like if my brother Daniel had been alive, or if my father, Schneor, had seen my children: Uriel (23) and the twins Tamara and Naama (16:30).
We must have been fighting about football and politics and celebrating each other."
Do you have a special childhood memory from the weekends?
We were a warm and united family.
On Friday afternoon, Mom would make a pile of schnitzels, bring hummus and pitas from the market and burn eggplants for a tahini salad.
Then we would go to Aunt Hannah's by the hand of Elijah, or as she would say 'the hand of Elijah', and she would make blintzes.
Since only I didn't like raisins, she used to make me some without raisins.
She saw me, the youngest of the brothers, and looked after me.
On Saturdays we would take a tour with my father in Jaffa Port, and he would show us where he and his twin brother, Grisha, came to Israel with nothing."
