"Protected Housing Association v. Ruthie Russo: Saying 'It tastes like protected housing' harms our operations"
Chairwoman Yuli Gat sent a letter, in which she expressed the union's complaint against an insulting statement, according to them, of a "next restaurant" judge in one of the trailers for the show
Ruthie Russo responded, "It's a joy that there are places that invest more in the culinary of this population."
The Association of Nursing Homes and Protected Housing in Israel against the "next restaurant": In a letter sent by chairwoman Yuli Gat and arrived at "Israel Today" it reads: "In the pre-broadcast trailer, which was distributed on all social networks and on television, it is described that the professional judge of the competition said 'food tastes like sheltered housing', i.e., closed institution food with low-level food."
"The tone chosen by the program's judge, Ruthie Russo, to describe her disappointment with the food that the contestant submitted immediately cancels our many years of activity to fight against the pits that exist in the field, because the sheltered housing houses run restaurants in the various homes in favor of the tenants with the highest level of chef dishes."
It added: "The service staff and house managers are struggling for the image of protected housing offering solutions for quality housing for the elderly, including eradication of loneliness, abundant leisure activities, high standard of living and more."
In Israel in recent years, more and more families and older people understand that loneliness is the most difficult disease in old age and view community places as a proven solution to the disease.
"Food is one of life's greatest pleasures, so we devote resources and efforts to serving the residents the finest food.
Most sheltered housing houses use professional chefs to build a menu.
We will be happy at all times to invite the judging staff to be impressed by the winning dishes served daily to tens of thousands of elderly people in Israel as well as on behalf of the chefs and restaurant staff in the sheltered housing houses we will ask for your apology and clarification.
Come together, the media and Israeli society, to encourage community housing for the health of the elderly."
Ruthie Russo said in response: "It's a joy that there are places that invest more in the culinary of this population, which certainly deserves excellent food in the advanced period of life.
I respect the hard work of cooks, cooks, chefs and chefs everywhere, even in assisted living."
"Double morals: in Russia you cancel a show but in Israel you didn't cancel?"
Nick Cave Responds to Criticism
The singer referred to the criticism that was hurled at him by a Turkish fan, who accused him of double standards
The singer responded: "The invasion of Ukraine is very different from the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
"
Nick Cave cancelled a concert in Russia earlier this week due to the war and declared that he "stands by Ukraine and prays that the madness will end soon".
In this, the esteemed Australian singer joined artists and bands such as Iggy Pop, Green Day and Franz Ferdinand, who also cancelled performances in the invading country.
But in Kiev's case his cancellation notice took a slightly different turn.
A Turkish fan named Ahmet plastered the singer he painted, as in 2017 Kiev refused to cancel two performances that took place in Israel, despite the criticism he received on behalf of pro-Palestinian organizations.
At the time of his visit to Israel, Kiev told local media: "In the end, I am here for two reasons: the first reason is because I love Israel and the Israelis, and the second reason is that I am against anyone who tries to censor and silence musicians."
This same Ahmet well remembered Kiev's statements in favor of music and against politicization.
The admirer even posted on the singer's personal, uncensored website, "The Red Hand Files", a poignant post in which he claimed that Israel is also an occupying country, and therefore the situation of Palestine is the same as that of Ukraine.
"What bothers me about your message about Ukraine," Ahmet wrote. "is that you did not support the Palestinians that way, who are also suffering from a brutal regime.
In fact, you described Israel as a functioning democracy, but in my opinion Israel is first and foremost the cause responsible for Palestinian suffering.
It makes me very sad, for you represent a double standard here," concluded the Turkish admirer.
But the story does not end here, as Kiev chose to reply to Ahmet in a long and detailed letter, in which he stressed that "Russia's invasion of Ukraine is very different from the ongoing conflict between Israel and the Palestinians.
The first situation is a one-state unprovoked attack on its neighbor, hoping to change the security order of the whole of Europe.
The second situation is a complex friction between two peoples.
While the conflicts are similar in that innocent people, who share a tragic fate, are forced to hide in shelters.
I feel a great deal of sympathy for all these communities – no matter where they are and who they are."
Kiev added that although he was not interested in detailing his views on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, he certainly supports the Palestinians as well, noting that in the past 20 years he has been attending fundraisers for them.
"But this is no time for debate, Ahmet, this is a time to unite and support the Ukrainians, who are currently taking place on their soil in a catastrophe.
I have great admirers in Russia, and I know that many Russians strongly oppose the actions of Putin's regime.
If I could play for them, I would."
In light of the decline in morbidity: Corona Projector will return to manage Ziv Hospital
Prof. Salman Zarka was appointed to the position in July 2021 and led the Corona treatment policy in the third and fourth wave
At the request of the Minister of Health Nitzan Horowitz, he will continue concurrently in his role as a Practor
Prof. Zarka: "Happy that the Omicron wave continues to fade, and yet it is our duty to prepare for another wave"
(Laughs)
Against the background of the decline in coronavirus morbidity, the Corona Projector, Prof. Salman Zarka, will return to manage Ziv Hospital in Safed on Sunday.
At the request of Health Minister Nitzan Horowitz, he will continue concurrently in his role as Viktor.
"I am happy for the citizens of Israel that the Omicron wave continues to fade and that we have received our normal lifestyle back," said Prof. Zarka, adding, "It is still our duty to prepare for another wave of morbidity as a result of the virus still being here, in Israel and around the world."
Prof. Zarka was appointed to the position in July 2021 and led the Corona treatment policy in the third and fourth waves.
From May 1, Israel has returned to a "between waves" state, which includes reducing most of the corona's arrays, while maintaining capabilities to carry out continuous checks and investigations, which will form the basis for action in the event a new variant is discovered.
Concealed morbidity
The Corona Campaign National Knowledge and Information Center report, published this morning, stated that "there is a decline in the average of new confirmed to below two thousand per day, on a weekly average, alongside a decrease in the number of hospitalized and hospitalized in a difficult situation".
However, they stressed that "there is an underlying morbidity of significant extent and in practice the number of infected is much higher.
The number of institutional tests carried out in the community (without weighing the tests returned from abroad, M.I.) - is low, and stands at less than 20,000 tests on a weekly average only.
The low scope of testing makes it difficult to identify and understand morbidity trends."
State Comptroller's Report: The actual budget for most years of operation of the pharmaceutical basket committee – less than the recommended budget
According to the report by Matanyahu Engelman, for more than 20 years of basket activity – the Ministry of Health did not supervise the activities of the committee
The report further states that the minutes of the meetings are published significantly late, if at all
Also, the auditor recommends increasing the transparency of the subcommittee's activities – and updating the basket work procedures
Another flaw that has been found concerns that since the committee began operations, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds for reports on the scope of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket – which would have allowed the analysis and review of the budget given to them.
The Pharmaceutical Basket Commission is one of the most influential public committees in our daily lives and health.
Each year, the Committee decides on new medicines to be given to the public free of charge through the HMOs – but a new State Comptroller's report released Tuesday warns that this has been in operation for more than 20 years without any control reports being made on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council overseeing and reviewing its activities.
"Israel Hayom" reporter Ran Reznik adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing revelations in "Israel Hayom" about the failures of the medicine basket.
According to the report by Matanyahu Engelman, he recommends "to carry out in the process of expanding the basket corrections and improvements, which will result in a more qualitative utilization of the health care basket budget that the public is entitled to".
Throughout the years of the existence of the supplement mechanism for the pharmaceutical basket, in the years 2021-1998, the state budget was supplemented with eight billion shekels of medicine – with the supplement moving annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add about 800 new medicines and technologies to the health care basket, at a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated for the basket's expansion was less than the scope of the requests.
In most of the committee's operating years (90% of the time), the budgetary supplement amount was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired supplement rate.
The reviewer notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the height of the annual addition with the aim of allowing certainty and long-term planning.
Engelmann further noted that "the transparency model in basket work is lacking".
Thus, for example, the procedure of the work of the basket committee states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the protocols are published in a delay of 160-109 days, when sometimes the final minutes of the meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in publishing the protocols harms the transparency of the decisions; as a result, the ability of the bidders – patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies – may be impaired to make repeated requests as soon as possible and relevant, after they have learned lessons from rejecting their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and revised their proposals and re-evaluated the feasibility of accepting them in the next round," the reviewer noted.
"The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules set in the procedure".
Out of thousands of submissions, only one financial comment was made.
Another review by Engelmann concerns a preliminary procedure of evaluating the technologies submitted to the pharmaceutical basket.
The comptroller found that about half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the postponement.
Another flaw concerns the activity of the subcommittee of the medicine basket that is closed to the media and the public, and in which patient numbers and costs of drugs are discussed.
The auditor recommends adding a public representative or examining the possibility of publicizing the discussions without confidential commercial details.
In the procedure under which the Health Services Basket Committee operates, it was determined that "economic assessment should be submitted" to a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one out of thousands of submissions have been submitted – and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, for the 2021-2019 Basket Committee hearings, applications were submitted to add to the Anti-Objection Medicines basket.
The report found that the requests did not include economic assessments, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing diseases caused by obesity or the ability to avoid gastric shortening surgeries.
It is further found that the decisions of the pharmaceutical basket committee are inconsistent with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, in 2019 the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparation for the treatment of the growth of chronic diseases as targets, but within the framework of decisions regarding the expansion of the basket no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The comptroller also warns that since 2011, services that are not the responsibility of the health funds are also included in the medicine basket, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health ("Third Supplement").
This is when the legal framework for this step is only regulated in retrospect.
In the last six years, NIS 74 million has been used from the addition to the medicine basket for these services.
Engelmann recommends that the Ministry of Health update the procedures of the basket work and also determine whether there is a need for a separate supplement for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that enter the drug basket are defined as "no extra cost drugs", the use of which does not cost the health funds an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The reviewer proposes to examine the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different and abbreviated route, so that the medicine basket can be updated several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no control over the use of expensive drugs.
The criticism also shows that since the work of the basket committee began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked health funds to report nor has it supervised the scope of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the ministry to analyze and audit the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports have been published relating to the years 2009-2006, and these have also been published with considerable delay (the latter was published this year and dealt with budget utilization from 2009-2007).
"The delay in conducting inspections may make it difficult to collect and analyze the data, irrelevant to the conclusions that arise from the examination after such a long period of time, to the improper pricing of the subcommittee and to make decisions based on non-final findings," the report said.
The ministry also does not review and supervise the uses of expensive drugs and has not carried out lessons.
This is 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in 2021-2016).
For this, the comptroller wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health perform individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the extent of their use compared to estimates.
Controls and analysis will make it possible to draw systemic conclusions about the work process of the basket committee and the subcommittee, and how to prepare estimates when pricing medicines and technologies and improving them."
"Shocking and Inconceivable": A heated discussion at the Health Committee about the poisoning at Beit Daphna
The indexes of the first deceased lettuce were normal ten minutes before her death
Chairman of the committee, MK Silman: "If the people there cared that the kitchen would be like home - it wouldn't look like this."
Ten minutes before the first lettuce about 40 years old from Beit Daphna in Holon died of food poisoning, she was taken with medical measures that were normal, the health committee said Tuesday.
"We have night care providers checking during the night and there's a nurse doing rounds.
There were a number of reports of diarrhea cases and the same tenant actually last time she was taken measures were 10 minutes before she stopped responding and they were normal.
She was monitored like the rest of the dikes with diarrhoea.
She's a nursing patient, we went to get a menoch to assist in her transfer and then the same tenant didn't respond.
We started CPR and called the nurse of the clinic," the daycare director described what happened last Sunday morning at the daycare center.
This is an event in which three residents died, six were hospitalized and a total of about a quarter of the residents (33 out of 131) had diarrhea to host contaminated surf meat.
The caretaker said this against the background of claims that death from food poisoning is indicative of neglect and lack of follow-up by the caregivers.
Dr. Naama Noss, Director of Epidemiology at the Tel Aviv Health Bureau, noted that "we cannot conclusively determine what the three hydrates died of.
Only blood tests were taken from them."
