I was there."
Gali Barmi, a representative of parents Bakim Israel: "We have complained in the past about the food and have not received the criticism."
Oren Hellman, founder of the Equal Chance Initiative for integrating people with disabilities, protested that the names of the deceased sponsors were not published: "Their names are not known at all.
Are they worth less?
We underestimate the lives of our children."
Suspicion of Wolfson omission: the surgeon caused a heart rupture - and the patient died.
This is the first procedure performed by Dr. Pras Abu Akar as the director of the hospital's thoracic surgery unit
The Chairman of the Committee of Physicians complained that the Headmistress, Dr. Engel, had been warned before his appointment
Hospital: "He's appreciated and experienced"
First publication: A horrific mistake occurred at the Wolfson Government Hospital in Holon, when during surgery the doctor performed a tear in the patient's heart, leading to his tragic death.
The surgery on an 83-year-old lung cancer patient was conducted on April 19.
This was the first operation performed by Dr. Pras Abu Aker at the hospital, after being appointed to the Director of the Chest Surgery Unit at Wolfson.
During the operation, designed to drain the area surrounding the patient's heart, the surgeon accidentally caused a large tear in the heart, which led to severe bleeding and caused the patient's death.
However, the unusual complication opened a Pandora's box, which raised difficult questions when it came to hospital management.
The Director of the Oncology Institute and Chairman of the Committee of Physicians, Dr. Ronen Brenner, demanded an investigation into the affair in a letter to the hospital director, Dr. Anat Engel.
In the letter, he made very serious claims about Dr. Engel's conduct and the appointment of Dr. Abu Akar after the previous unit's director, Dr. Benny Zuckerman, moved to Sheba Hospital in Tel Hashomer.
A huge hole in the heart
According to Dr. Brenner's letter, the patient has been lucid, functional and treated by him for the past four years.
He recently had an infestation of the disease, and an abnormal build-up of fluid within the pericardium, within which the heart muscle was found.
Also, surgeon Dr. Abu Akar was impressed that he could perform the surgery.
According to the complaint, the operation had a serious malfunction, and Dr. Hagai Dekel, director of the heart and chest surgery department at Wolfson, who was at the time in the operation of a child in the next room, "was urgently called to the operating table and saw a huge hole in the heart."
According to him, the heart was drained of blood, the blood pressure was zero, and the surgical approach was wrong.
In addition, Dr. Brenner said that Dr. Dekel approached him and told him that Dr. Abu Akar was not professionally and personally suited to manage a chest surgery unit at Wolfson.
However, despite his explicit warnings and although he was supposed to be the direct director of the thoracic surgeon, Dr. Engel made a tender without sharing it and accepted Dr. Abu Akar for the position.
He added: "This is an uncomplicated procedure, which lasts a few minutes," and added: "It is impossible not to refer to the flawed process of accepting Dr. Abu Akar for the position.
The question arises whether there is a direct responsibility of Engel for the failure of the operation and the death of the patient."
Experienced surgeon
Information and claims were raised to Israel Today by other senior doctors who reinforce the questions raised in the case of Dr. Ronen Brenner.
Dr. Mordechai Shimonov, chief surgical officer at Wolfson, responded to Brenner's complaint, writing that Dr. Abu Akar is "one of the more experienced surgeons in the country, but a relatively young breast surgeon".
He also added that he was elected in a proper tender and Dr. Dekel took no part in it, in accordance with his declarations of his desire to "disengage" from the chest unit.
He added: "I wasn't part of the process either, and I may have been meant to be.
Dr. Shimonov wrote that Dr. Pras Abu Akar began working on 10 April and was entitled to 100 days of grace, "All hospital doctors were impressed by his professionalism and motivation and willingness to work.
He has already performed dozens of cases of a similar procedure, and unfortunately the current case ended as it unfortunately ended.
Wolfson Hospital said in response: "We share the family's grief.
This is a patient of oncologist Dr. Ronen Brenner.
The chest surgeon mentioned in the article is an esteemed surgeon with many years of experience, and was selected in a tender to manage a chest surgery unit associated with the surgery department at Wolfson Hospital.
"According to Dr. Haggai Dekel, his quoted remarks are inaccurate and have been taken out of context.
It should be noted that this is a patient who was unfortunately in a very difficult situation.
The hospital is looking into the details of the case transparently, and the Ministry of Health is familiar with the details of the case."
