A model for healing: three senior doctors tell about their mentors
Prof. Galia Rahav misses the wit and wisdom of the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, especially during the plague
Dr. Shlomi Kadosh does not forget, even from the height of his position, the push from the late Prof. Shaul Sukenik
And Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev thanks Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld for the lesson in identifying with the patients
Three key people in hospitals write about who inspired and encouraged them to be better, as therapists and as human beings.
Three senior doctors, three life and professional teachers: on the occasion of Israeli Doctor's Day, "Israel Hayom" invited Prof. Galia Rahav, Dr. Shlomi Kadesh and Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev to recall the characters who accompanied them at the beginning of the road – and helped them become who they are today.
Prof. Galia Rahav, Director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Sheba
About Prof. Marvin Shapira z"l
The meeting that opened my eyes - and changed my life
Had I not met the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, who was the director of the infectious disease unit at Hadassah Hospital, I would probably have remained an expert physician in internal medicine.
He was the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and influenced me to engage in it.
I met him in the halls of Hadassah, E. Back in the 1980s.
For a moment I didn't think I'd leave the interior, as I liked the treatment of the patient himself; but Prof. Shapira showed me that the field of infectious diseases was also expressed in neurology, also in the interior, and in virtually every area.
I thank him for bringing me into this field.
All along, I loved his investigative approach, an approach that goes down to the root of the problem.
The discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor in all his soul, who loved the sick and taught me not to take things for granted and to look deeply into everything.
He was a real and honest man, devoid of ego, qualities I loved very much.
At first, when I was asked to choose a doctor who was a role model for me and who influenced me the most, I intended to choose my father, the late Dr. Joseph Rakover, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who influenced me to go to medicine - but he also reminds me of Marvin Chapera.
Both, for example, coined proverbs that doctors use to this dayfor example, "Tishu Iz de Ishio", i.e., taking a tissue biopsy from the affected organ allows one to know which drugs are worth giving; or "Won Yo Hewes Itt, Yu Luz Itt", designed to explain that overuse of antibiotics leads to the bacteria becoming resistant to it.
The late Prof. Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked in Hadassah and fathered two daughters.
He died about a year ago, and when I visited his family at seven I cried.
He was somethinga witty, wise epidemiologist, who volunteered for everything.
He never complained, not even during his illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the team to treat the plagues, and he was greatly missed during this time.
If he were with us today, I'm sure I would have consulted him, and I'm sure he would have been one of the leaders of the pest control team.
brought to light: Meital Yasor Beit-Or
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh, Director of Soroka Hospital
About Prof. Shaul Soknik z"l
A teacher and friend who supported me and raised generations of doctors
(Laughs)
I first met the late Prof. Shaul Soknik when I was a fourth-year medical student, and I came to a round of internal medicine in the Department of Internal Medicine that he ran.
Later I also returned to the department in rotation in the sixth year, and I did the final work of the medical school under his direction, writing a computer simulation on a patient with polyarthritis (multiple joint inflammation).
Shaul has influenced every significant node in my professional life for 20 years, and has been the most significant person in shaping my character as a doctor; not only professionally, but also – and most importantly – personally and humanely.
During the internship, I debated between family medicine and internal medicine, and consulted with him about choosing the internship.
Eventually I chose to specialize in internal medicine with him in Soroka.
During the internship he provided me with constant guidance, in a variety of ways – in scientific writing (sorry Saul, I didn't persevere enough), in contact with patients, in working in a multi-professional team – an area in which the department excelled – and in fact, in every aspect related to medicine.
To this day, I recognize in me, as a doctor and as a manager, characteristics that come from Saul.
When I finished my internship and debated whether to travel for a period of study abroad, Saul pushed and directed me, assisting me with letters of recommendation and advice on how to behave.
The training period was a very important time for my professional development, and without Saul's support and push I'm not sure this would have happened.
On my return, when I received an offer to join the hospital management, again Saul was the one who supported and assisted.
We later worked together through complex periods in the Internal Medicine Division.
Saul knew how to wonderfully integrate the teacher, the manager, the friend, and the teammate, without his various roles interfering with each other.
I strive to succeed like him in this special combination.
He raised generations of students, interns and interns, who are now throughout the medical system in Israel, and commemorate their excellent work and memory.
I'm honored to be appointed with this group.
Brought to light: Ilya Yegorov
Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev, Director of Schneider Children's Medical Center
About Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld
The man who taught me medicine, and especially listening.
Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld, founder and former director of the ICU at Schneider Children's Medical Center, taught me to be an ICU doctor, but more than that – he taught me to think.
The obvious thing I've learned from him is to take care of the most complex, the sickest children.
The children, some of whom were healthy just a moment ago, are now between life and death.
The obvious is to have very difficult, perhaps the most difficult, conversations with families who never imagined they would get into these complex situations in an intensive care unit with their children.
Sounds strange, but it's the obvious.
But I learned things from him that are even deeper and more profound.
In hindsight, since I am a doctor she manages and manages who is a doctor, it is clear to me today the connection between the worlds; the education I received from Dr. Sheinfeld connects them.
Dr. Schinfeld taught me to listen attentively to many things: listen to the children, listen to the monitor, listen to the nurses, to the young and old caregiver teams, and listen to the parents.
All of this needs to be done not only to communicate more correctly and more successfully, but to constantly gather much information that can prevent the next deterioration.
The preventive processes in the care of children are everywhere, and of course in intensive care as well.
Listening and talking stimulates a deeper understanding, both on the part of the caring staff and on the part of the patients and their families.
My understanding today as a manager is that these insights are also true in looking at an entire system.
The more in-depth and rigorous understanding there is, the more accurate the decision-making process will be, the better suited to the situation, and most importantly – early enough to prevent future, immediate or distant damage.
That's why Dr. Tommy Sheinfeld is so much more than an inspirational character to me.
He's a man who taught me a lot of medicine, but mostly taught me to think fast and accurately, to listen - and then to apply.
Published by: Yaron Doron
