Participate in the preparation of the news: Yuri Yalon
Medical Malpractice at Different Birth Stages
In order to win damages, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused due to the same negligence
Birth is one of the most joyous and exciting events in a family's life.
Unfortunately, however, births sometimes result in serious damage caused to the birther or newborn as a result of medical staff negligence.
In cases where the birth ended with bodily harm, the newborn or the mother, there is room to examine the sequence of events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
An attorney specializing in the field of medical malpractice will examine whether there have been any flaws in the medical staff's conduct during the various birth stages which have caused damage and the more he sees fit, the more he turns to consult with a medical specialist in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every mistake in treatment on the part of the medical staff arises to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that the binge was negligent.
When is it negligent?
When the doctor's error was due to incompetence or deviation from the reasonable level of caution, and the lack of skill and deviation from the accepted level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused had the doctor not done so.
In this article we will examine the various birth stages, explain what complications may occur in each of the stages and when they arise to medical malpractice.
Axis phase
The axial phase lasts on average between 8 and 14 hours.
At this point the cervix gradually opens (to allow the embryo to pass at the time of birth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most cases of medical negligence during the labor phase deal with the failure to identify fetal distress prior to birth, which has caused damage to the newborn that is sometimes even manifested in cerebral palsy.
Cerebral palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy may be caused by a non-recognition or delayed detection of a subnatal stimulator, which is manifested in an oxygen supply failure to the fetal brain tissue.
As a rule, monitoring the birthing mother's condition and correct deciphering of the monitor that monitors fetal heart activity should lead to early identification of fetal distress development, allowing the medical team to act quickly and extract the newborn before being irreversibly injured.
Cases in which the medical team ignores signs that indicate the fetus is suffering from a lack of oxygen or that the team is not correctly interpreting the data in front of it and in particular the fetal monitor or reacting late to the distress expressed in the monitor – can be negligent.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by the fall of the umbilical cord as well as a ruptured uterus that has not been detected in a timely manner.
Even in these difficult events, it is worthwhile to find out whether the medical team has acted properly.
For example, Adv. Anna Rafe Liganza, of Caspi Sror & Co., who specializes in representing victims of medical malpractice, says that her office handled the claim of a child who was injured during his birth after the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac when the fetus' head was too high, thus leading to the fall of the umbilical cord (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetus' head) and to damage the oxygen supply to the fetus's brain (as a result of severe injury of the umbilical cord).
In another case, the lawyer said that her office had filed a claim due to severe medical negligence of the maternity ward staff in a large hospital which during the birth did not identify at the time clear signs that necessitated a real suspicion that the mother was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the surgical scarring area of her previous pregnancy.
The fetus that was ejaculated through the rupture in its mother's womb into the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until its rescue late on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child had a complex neurological disability.
It should be emphasized that in order to win compensation, plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal link between the negligence of the medical staff that resulted in the failure to identify the defect and the damage caused to the newborn, i.e. that the damage was caused due to said negligence and not by any other reason or factor.
The examination of the causal relationship will be carried out through the examination of medical indicators that according to the medical literature only in their existence there is a causal link between the abstinence and the brain injury.
Among other things, the measures of the pH level in the fetus' blood, its Apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic injury, and more are examined.
The passing of the fetus
The active birth stage
The active birth stage begins when the cervical opening reaches a diameter of 10 cm and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical phase.
Suspension at birth and avoidance of carrying out a cesarean section
In some cases, dysfunctional birth develops, i.e., lack of progress of the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a cesarean section, in order to prevent various damage that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in birth.
"There are cases where failure to perform a caesarean section on time may cause irreparable damage to the fetus," Attorney Rafe-Liganza explained to us.
"For example, we have conducted a medical malpractice claim of neonatal death caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
Contrary to any recognized medical practice, the medical staff were not able to identify the fetal distress and perform a cesarean section despite particularly slow progress of birth.
The delay in performing the operation caused multiple systemic damage to the birthing system which eventually led to her death shortly after her birth."
Malpractice at a vacuum birth
In situations where a mother or fetus faces a significant danger requiring a particularly rapid termination of birth, a vacuum birth (empty shulpan) is sometimes performed.
In this process, a "dome" vacuum is attached to the embryo's head and forcefully pulls out the embryo.
Naturally, this action involves risks and can cause damage to both the fetus and the mother and therefore requires great caution, accuracy and skill.
In these events medical malpractice may be manifested in the fact that the doctor does not follow the binding guidelines and carries out the action despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the fetal head is too high in the pelvis, or performs it for a longer period of time than is permitted or when despite the failure of numerous attempts, the doctor continues to repeat the action more than the number of attempts allowed.
In these cases if the negligent vacuum operation has caused the newborn damage – among other things, it can cause skull damage and bleeding that can cause brain damage – there is room for a tort claim to be filed.
ERB Named Paralysis
Irv's palsy is an innate nerve injury to the brachial plexus (a nerve junction connecting the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during labor it is appropriate to check whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetrician team.
The injury manifests itself in the weakness of the hand muscles and can reach up to full paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of a'shoulder-bleed' - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the fetus's shoulders are locked inside the birth canal after its head has been out.
When should you suspect that paralysis is the result of medical negligence?
In cases where assessing the weight of the fetus indicated that it is a macarosomal fetus, meaning that it is expected to be born at a weight exceeding 4.5 kilograms and in accordance with the guidelines it is preferable to deliver the mother by cesarean section.
When the weight of the newborn is over 4 kilograms, a cesarean section should be considered in light of the risk factors including gestational diabetes and the second stage of delivery.
In the event that the medical team ignores an abnormal weight assessment of the fetus or other risk factors and chooses to continue vaginal birth and realizes the risk of shoulder arrhythmia and ERB paralysis, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical negligence.
Indeed, in CA 2694/90, the Supreme Court held that "the risk of shoulder stenosis occurring during labor can be foreseen to one degree or another of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is a concern of its occurrence, is by conducting a cesarean section".
Placental exit phase
Separating the placenta from the uterus and excreting it occurs due to uterine contraction after the newborn exit and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process usually lasts up to half an hour from the time of the baby's departure and usually occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the placenta exit, the medical team will check to see if it has come out intact or if any placenta parts remain in the uterus.
As part of this phase, complications may occur that may cause serious damage to the mother.
One of the known complications as a result of remaining placental residues in the uterus is called "Aschermann's syndrome", the scarring of the uterine wall resulting from inflammation caused by leaving placental residues in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the uterine mucosa in a way that does not allow for the implantation of pregnancy.
Therefore, in cases in which the medical team did not identify that any placenta residue remained or did not take all measures to prevent uterine mucosa injury despite the suspicion that placenta residue in the uterus may have been medical negligence and the case is worthy of a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
The Birthing Death
The death of a child during childbirth is a fairly rare euro.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy to the whole family unfortunately becomes the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the mother on time or respond late to such bleeding.
"For example...", said Attorney Rafe-Ligenza, "our office filed a claim concerning the death of a child, when in that case the medical staff ignored and did not respond to the worrisome vital signs of the birthing mother, for long hours, and was late in diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the underlying disease she was suffering from."
"In another case...", said attorney Rafe-Liganza, "our office represented the relatives of a woman who died after the birth of twins due to bleeding that originated in the C-section that was not sewn properly.
In the same case, the mother complained of severe pain and weakness after the operation, but the medical staff did not properly address her complaints and clinical condition, responding late only after her body systems began to collapse, which resulted in her death."
Loss of uterus
In severe cases, medical malpractice at birth may lead to a hysterectomy, says attorney Rafe Lingza: "Our firm conducted a lawsuit against a hospital that is based on hysterectomy due to medical malpractice after birth.
In the same case, a 31-year-old woman lost her uterus due to the lack of adequate treatment for massive bleeding observed by the medical staff after birth and was nevertheless not taken during the actions that could have prevented the damage."
What are the damages awarded in medical malpractice claims at birth?
Newborn compensation for injury due to medical negligence at birth includes many damage components, with the most significant amounts being given for pain and suffering, nursing and wage care, loss of wages and pension to the injured and even to his parents and other damage components.
The compensation awarded to an injured minor for salary and pension losses is calculated in most cases based on the average wage in the economy.
In addition, the compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation accessories, the cost of adjusting housing for the needs of the baby, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined in each case and according to its circumstances," says Attorney Rafe-Liganza, and she further states that "today most claims on the grounds of medical malpractice are supplemented by a compromise that weighs the chance and risk that each party has in the management of the proceeding," but the lawyer added that "there are cases in which the proceeding ends only in a judgment, so if the claim is not denied, the plaintiffs will receive a full compensation for all their damages and, for example, in a court case that has been conducted."
In conclusion
Medical malpractice at birth is undoubtedly every family's nightmare.
In these cases a proper legal examination of the chain of events that resulted in the tragic outcome, by a skilled attorney in the management of claims on the grounds of medical malpractice, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
This is the reason for the prevalence of keratoconus eye disease in the south
A study found that there is a link between the development of the disease and the marriage of relatives
The highest incidence was found in the Bedouin sector
Expert: "It is possible that in any sector with many weddings between cousins, there is a high incidence of the disease."
Keratoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes some vision impairments.
It is very important to diagnose it as soon as possible, and find proper solutions to prevent worsening of the condition.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted to help understand how the disease develops, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new studies give a research basis for suspicion of keratoconus eye disease being a genetic disease.
A recent study, which dealt with transforming the shape of the cornea from a dome to an engraver, found that the cause of the disease and weakness of the cornea and its deformation is associated with an enzyme imbalance, which could result in free radicals damaging the proteins in the cornea – and its structure will change.
The source of this enzyme deficiency is genetic, a fact that reinforces the hypothesis that keratocanus is a hereditary disease.
According to Prof. Ariella Gordon-Shag, head of the Optometric Sciences Department at Hadassah Academic College, "In a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, the prevalence of keratoconus was found to be 3.2%.
The highest incidence was among students from the Bedouin sector – 20% had keratoconus, but there was a small relative sample."
The researcher added that this is an unsurprising finding: "There is a large prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies we found that close marriages are a risk factor for keratoconus disease.
So in any sector with lots of weddings between cousins, we may find high prevalence."
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unequivocal conclusion: in cases where a family history of keratoconus disease appears, all family members should undergo a proper eye exam as soon as possible.
According to Arza Prochter, a B.Sc. clinical optometrist, "there is a tenfold appeal to the clinic from remote periphery areas, mainly from the southern region, versus the center".
Fruchter adds that "in the past decade I have noticed that most patients are evacuated from the periphery, especially from the Beersheba area.
This is mainly due to the high prevalence of marriage within the family (mainly in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of proper treatment of the problem."
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Prochter explains that keratoconus usually develops in adolescence or late teens (ages 16-15 or 20).
The disease includes a decrease in vision, parallel to an increase in the cylinder.
Keratoconus patients indicate distorted and/or blurred vision of characters and objects.
These signs worsen with the development of the disease, which often develops slowly and gradually over the years.
However, the disease may also develop at a rapid rate and reach its peak in just a few months.
Many patients even show increased sensitivity to light.
About three years after the operation in Gaza - the IDF revealed the name of Lt. Col. M.; Bennett: "Now, the people know the face of the hero of Israel"
Mahmoud Khair al-Din of the village of Hurfish is a lieutenant colonel who was killed in an operation in Khan Yunis
Head of Military Intelligence: "He deserves the publicity, his family and his children"
Later on, the possibility of publishing Lt. Col. Emmanuel Moreno's photograph from the General Staff Patrol will be examined.
About three and a half years after the operation that took place in Khan Yunis, the IDF today permits the publication that the killed in the operation, Lt. Col. M, is the late Lt. Col. Mahmoud Khair ad-Din from the village of Hurfish in the north.
He was 41 years old in Nuplo.
Prime Minister Bennett said after the publication: "It has been three and a half years since the late Lieutenant Colonel Mahmoud Hir al-Din fell in battle in a secret operation in Khan Yunis, and only now are we allowed to reveal his name and thank him for his contribution and dedication to state security.
"Mahmoud was a fighter in a paratrooper patrol and later grew up in the army ranks to be a lieutenant colonel in the IDF's Special Operations Division.
The hero of Israel who was decorated after his death in the IDF Chief of Staff."
He also said: "I told him at his funeral and now the people of Israel have a right to know him, the name and face of the hero of Israel, Lieutenant Colonel Mahmoud Hir Al-Din, openly.
The environment looked up to him.
Since the operation, the IDF has banned the publication of his name for security reasons, and today, after a discussion conducted by the head of the intelligence division, Maj. Gen. Aharon Haliva, with representatives of the military censors, and with the consent of his family members, it was decided to publish his name and picture.
Mahmoud Khair al-Din, a hero of Israel, was born on December 28, 1977 in the village of Hurfish in the Upper Galilee, the eldest son of his parents Ahmad and Nasira, with seven brothers and sisters.
He's a member of the Druze community.
He was married to Nahad and father of two sons.
He served as an officer, combatant and commander in the Special Operations Division of the Intelligence Division.
Throughout his life, Khir ad-Din was a social leader, and the environment looked up to him.
By 9th grade, he was attending school in the village of Hurfish, and then moved to the military boarding school at the Reali School in Haifa.
In October 1997, he enlisted in a paratroopers' cruiser, and in 2000 he graduated from the Officers' School.
In 2002 he was located by the Special Operations Directorate in A.N. and moved to serve there.
During his service, he completed a bachelor's degree in law at the College of Management and a master's degree in education and business administration at the University of Haifa.
In 2002 he met his wife, Nahed, and in 2004 they married.
Their first son was born in 2009, a year during which he established with his friends an association that works to promote the status of the Druze community in Israel.
In 2010, he joined Aharai and began to guide a group in the village of Hurfish, after he made sure that the organization would start operating in the Druze villages to encourage youth to enlist.
In 2013, his second son was born.
Military Intelligence Chief Colonel Aharon Haliva explained the reasons for the decision to reveal his name: "It is time we become on the issue of exposing the name of Mahmoud Khair ad-Din, the hero of Israel.
We finished work and came to the conclusion that there is no security impediment to publishing his name and picture.
It also deserves him, his family and his children," he noted.
"Extraordinary Educator and Leader"
"Thanks to many operations he is nothing short of a hero in my eyes," said Chaliva champion.
"He has a significant contribution, which has courage and composure, to the State of Israel.
He deserves to have the right place for him."
He added: "I didn't know him personally, but he was an exceptional educator, educator and leader - not only on the operational side, but also on my values."
General Haliva noted that he would also later examine whether to publish the photograph of another hero, Lt. Col. Emmanuel Moreno of the General Staff Patrol, who fell during the Second Lebanon War, and his picture was not allowed to be published.
The operation in Khan Yunis took place on 11 November 2018.
The operation was the culmination of long months of meticulous preparations that the intelligence community took part in.
In the command squad of the operation sat the then Chief of Staff, Lt. Gen. Gadi Eisenkot, then Head of Military Intelligence, Major General Tamir Heyman and then Chief of the Shin Bet, Nadav Argaman.
The purpose of the operation has not yet been allowed to be published, and the IDF has emphasized that this is an action whose intelligence value is invaluable.
But in the Arab media, hindsight radio equipment was presented that, according to the Palestinians, was left behind by the forces.
According to Hamas, the operation was intended to install listening devices.
According to reports, on the day of the incident, the force was traveling in two vehicles.
The fighters were arrested at a checkpoint deployed by Hamas members, and something about their behavior aroused the suspicion of Hamas operatives.
The activists surrounded the vehicle and began questioning its passengers.
The field investigation took about 45 minutes, during which time it became increasingly aggressive.
When the force realized that it was in a problematic situation, Lt. Col. Khair ad-Din managed to distract Hamas members, and in a split second the commander of the force, Lt. Col. A, was able to open fire.
From the fire, three Hamas members were killed, and unfortunately, Lt. Col. Khir al-Din was also killed.
Ten months after the difficult incident, the Chief of Staff, Lt. Col. Aviv Kochavi, decided to accept the recommendation of the citation committee and grant the Chief of Staff's commendation to three of the fighters in the incident deep in the Gaza Strip - including the late Lt. Col. Khir al-Din.
The commander of the combat force and another combatant on the team were also given a commendation.
The army said in a statement at the time that Lt. Col. M had received the commendation "for his activity in the operation with his crew, in enemy territory, with determination, composure and courage, for the protection of his comrades.
He then acted out of initiative and striving for touch, taking a forward role in taking over the enemy and acting resourcefully to advance the takeover.
Consider moving from tweezer operations to extensive operation
Israel needs to ask itself, again, if it is wrong to change policy vis--vis the Jenin sector
During Ramadan, Israel refrained from doing so, fearing that Jenin would fuel and ignite the West Bank, but that Jenin gunmen might leave it no choice.
The stormy weekend we've been through teaches that even though the month of Ramadan is behind us, the territory is still more volatile than ever.
It will take great effort and common sense to pass through the two upcoming memorials: the Nakba Day which is today (Sunday), and Jerusalem Day which will be celebrated in two weeks.
Quite a few factors will stand by in an attempt to torpedo back into sanity.
In their heads, as always, are the elements of terrorism, which concentrate a special effort in an attempt to preserve the violent atmosphere of the past few weeks.
Evidence of this was given during the arrest operation in which a SWAT fighter was killed two days ago, the late Brig. Gen. Noam Raz.
Fighters who took part in the battle in Jenin testified that they do not remember such a scope of shooting and violence – evidence not only of the enormous amount of weapons on the ground, but also of the willingness to use it.
This requires Israel to ask itself, again, if it is wrong to change policy vis--vis the Jenin sector, and to move from small, intelligence-based tweezers to a mass-based operation.
During Ramadan, Israel refrained from doing so, fearing that Jenin would fuel and ignite the West Bank and the entire arena in its wake; even now, the defense establishment prefers to act selectively, when necessary, in order to avoid incendiary action, but Jenin militants may leave it no choice.
Produce the lessons for future events.
Raz's death in battle is the best answer Israel can give anyone who claims to have deliberately killed Al Jazeera journalist Shirin Abu Aqla.
Operational activity is a dangerous matter for those who participate in it, and for those who attend the scene.
The IDF takes enormous risks to its forces in order to avoid harming innocent people as much as possible, and sometimes pays for it with the lives of combatants.
This is indicative of high morals, but it also has an operational-intelligence value: a terrorist who was captured aliveas happened in Jenin the day beforeis an excellent source of information about weapons, attacks and other terrorists; this is information that is usually not otherwise obtainable, and through which the next attacks can be thwarted.
The IDF acted correctly when it published its interim investigation into Abu Aqla's death yesterday, making it clear that it was not possible to determine at this stage who caused her death.
In the absence of Palestinian cooperation, it is doubtful whether it will be possible to reach an unequivocal bottom line in the affair.
In any case, nothing seems to convince the convinced: the world has already rushed to condemn Israel without bothering to balance it with a word of empathy for the victims of Palestinian terrorism – the original ground on which the IDF is constantly operating in Jenin.
As always, the nature of such stories perish.
World public opinion is busy with ripeness and moving on, certainly as Ukraine continues to rampage a much more intense war.
Therefore, it is a pity that Israel insisted on giving the affair of Abu Aqla's death more unnecessary moments of exposure, with the police's unsuccessful treatment of her funeral.
Even if Abu 'Aqla's family did not live up to the early summaries, there should have been a little more braking ability expected from the policemen who accompanied the funeral procession, and certainly less excitement from the Palestinian flags that were raised there.
Responsibilities: Act to calm the situation.
Good did the Minister of Homeland Security and the Police Commissioner who ordered the investigation of the incident.
It seems to lack sufficient preparation and clear instructions, but it is disturbing that this is the second time this has happened to the police in a short time, and in two different districts.
Also in the attack in Dizengof, the police failed to manage the incident, isolate the scene, and handle the media.
The Commission of Inquiry will do well not only to analyze the conduct of police officers at the funeral itself, but also to draw lessons and conclusions that will allow for more successful handling of similar events in the future.
Alongside the internal handling of the police, it also undertakes to give consideration to the conduct of elected officials who have lost way and direction.
In the Knesset, Israel currently serves several members who appear to be a danger to democracy.
They are on the left and right, using their immunity not to challenge the country, but to harm it.
MK Ofer Kasif is the latest example of this; if no measures are taken against him – including a prosecution for assaulting a police officer – the state will encourage the next elected official to further officer his actions.
Such moves, which are a defensive democracy, are essential in the explosiveness of this period, with elements in the background seeking to exploit the situation for political purposes.
Anyone with common sense in their head is expected to rise above all of these, and act to calm the situation; otherwise, Israel could quickly slide into escalation in the face of enemies from outside, and worse, in the face of domestic adversaries.
Police official: "Government policy and goal setting are needed here"
Israel Police may have launched an operation to eradicate the phenomenon of illegal aliens, but the road is still long
There is not a single factor in the State of Israel that includes this whole issue."
"If you want to address the phenomenon of illegal aliens, government policy is required, and from it goals, tasks, and responsibilities must be derived.
Today there is no single party in the State of Israel that includes this entire issue," a senior police official told Israel Today.
Until a month and a half ago, prior to the escalation in the security situation, the phenomenon was expressed in about 20,000 to 30,000 NIS that enter daily through the breaches in the fence.
In addition, between 100 and 110,000 Palestinians with work permits enter work daily in Israel through 34 supervised crossings.
It should be noted that Palestinians have been employed in Israel since the end of the Six-Day War, and the number of permits in each branch is limited in the quota set by the political echelon in accordance with the security, economic and political situation in the State of Israel.
Permits are issued by the IDF through the Coordination and Liaison Administration.
In light of this, the Shin Bet is not necessarily a Palestinian whose entry is prohibited due to criminal involvement or connection to terrorist attacks, but in many cases it is Palestinians whose entry was forbidden because they do not meet the quota of permits allowed.
It should be emphasized that those who carried out the attacks in Ariel, Dizengof and Balad were indeed considered to be Shin Bet, but were not supervised, because they had not previously committed any criminal offense that required security officials to monitor their movements.
"Therefore there is no significance to their entry through the breaches in the fence," says a senior security official, "Those who wish to carry out an attack can enter the country through the supervised crossings as well, and there have been such cases in the past.
Thousands of arrests
In the wake of the attack in Elad and in light of multiple alerts to the attacks, the police launched a large-scale operation to locate illegal residents.
By the end of the week, 16,000 people had been arrested.
Of these, about 600 were investigated and criminal cases were opened for them, and about 200 were imprisoned.
According to the police prosecution policy, proceedings against an illegal detainee are only carried out against criminals who stumble or people who repeat the act repeatedly (recidivists).
An illegal resident who was arrested for the first time is interrogated, documented and returned to the territories.
This is sometimes repeated a second time as well, but only a third time has he been arrested, jailed, and indicted for illegal stay.
According to the law, if an illegal resident is caught within 50 to 100 meters of either side of the separation fence, treatment is carried out by the military prosecution.
Data that reached Israel Hayom shows that in 2021, 40,010 illegal residents were treated by the police, from traveller and melamines.
7,405 illegal aliens have been arrested and 19,533 have opened a criminal case.
The number of employers, conveyors and lenders treated by the police in 2021 was 6,537.
469 were arrested, and 5,640 criminal cases were opened.
"The foundations of the Shin Bet phenomenon are not dependent on the police, not on the IDF, not on Israeli society and not on Palestinian society.
They depend on other factors," says a senior law enforcement official.
"In order to address this phenomenon, they must be motivated to go out to work in Israel, and on the Israeli side, they must be charged a price that will prevent them from crossing the fence.
Sources involved in the matter argue that failure to collect the price is due, among other things, to a lack of places of detention and the fact that arrests are only made when there are related offences or that it is a recidivist.
Legal officials claim that the decision to exact a price from Shin Bet only starting from its third arrest was also made in part because the courts cannot deal with the number of arrests being made every day.
Anyone who examines the punishment will also find that it is not deterring."
There is great complexity
Shabak," says a police official, "is a complex man."
He could be the father of a family that came into the country to work to earn a few shekels and come back.
This is the basic platform, on which many types of Shin Bets are dressed to enter the country in order to commit criminal offenses or terrorist attacks."
It may be adult or minor.
In the past, police have caught illegal 16-year-olds and even children 8 and 10 years old sent by their parents to road intersections to earn a few shekels a day from customs.
"It also makes the matter complicated, because in such cases we have to bring the parents and charge them with neglect," says a senior police officer.
Most Palestinians are employed in Israel in manual labor.
The most unusual are electrical works or advanced construction works.
In the past, there were also local authorities who employed incursions in garbage disposals, mainly in the north.
Out of 34 crossings, there are about 18 major crossings.
There are passages of vehicles and goods, there are passages that pass through only people and there are passages that are both.
All crossings are supervised by the IDF and the transit authority.
The ISAs are usually driven into the country by private drivers, as this is easy money.
"There are those who do this for a living and there are gangs whose main occupation is the transportation of shalabim," a senior police official says, "usually most of them are Israeli Arabs, who speak the same language and correspond with them.
It can reach 100 shekels up to 300 shekels per person.
Registered companies do not engage in this, because if the company is caught, it is doomed to close."
Police emphasize that under certain conditions, the passage of the ISA can be considered an offence.
"A taxi driver who works with licenses in accordance with licensing and insurance, who collects Palestinians at fixed points and at regular hours, including an orderly reservation, does not break the law," says a senior police official, "who knows that he drives ISA, usually picks them up in the middle of the night at hiding points, including downloading at hidden points.
Most of these guys drive a car from Chukmec because they know they're being impounded so they'd rather ride in an old car."
