"A criminal investigation should be launched against her": Haifa City Comptroller on serious charges against Einat Kalish Rotem
The city comptroller's report presents an apparent concern for the criminal conduct of Dr. Einat Kalish Rotem against former city officials and political opponents: employee surveillance and inflated payment to an accountant's office for carrying out the investigations
"The hard findings emerging from the report require the opening of a criminal investigation"
The City of Haifa received no response.
Surveillance of city employees and political opponents and inflated payment to an accountant's office for carrying out the investigations, "at the expense of the public register".
A report by Haifa Municipality Comptroller Ofer Tal published yesterday (Tuesday), presents an apparent fear of criminal offenses by Mayor Dr. Einat Kalish Rotem against former municipal officials, municipal employees, and political opponents.
According to the suspicion, Kalish met with the accounting firm of Barlev & Co. and asked for an investigative review.
The investigations were conducted under names and codes given to the former city treasurer, and a code name given to councilwoman Sophie Nakash, and examined whether the tenders between the municipality and a company owned by Nakash's family are kosher to Mehadrin.
It also emerges from the auditor's report that there is a complete disorder and lack of control over the work of the accountant with whom Kleish met.
The city treasurer is the municipal official whose job is to concentrate and synchronize the work of the accountant and the municipal departments and the data collected by the accountant were not transferred to him.
This meant that no one in the municipality was aware of all the projects carried out by the accountant, and the scope of work required in each of them.
Moreover, the hours reports submitted by the accountant have not been confirmed in many cases as required.
A situation was created in which the scope of the issues in which the accountant was involved increased disproportionately, with great intervention in the routine conduct of the municipality, without any supervision and surveillance from the municipality.
At the conclusion of the report, the review recommended stopping the unpaid payments to the accountant until material was received detailing his work on each of the issues examined.
In addition, invoices submitted to the Haifa Municipality were under codes such as "Gatekeepers", an information store, a fish shop, an investigative review for the mayor and a procurement investigative review report.
Shortly thereafter, the city's attorney, Yamit Klein, noted that the mayor herself had signed the payment confirmation in its place.
"Not invited by any review report and I don't know what it's about," she wrote.
It was also revealed that the cost of the investigative audit is about two million shekels, of which one and a half million shekels were paid and about half a million shekels remain to be paid, from the tax money of the Haifa public.
Former city treasurer Jackie Vakim responded: "These despicable acts that were done for the purpose of tarnishing my name and the name of elected officials at the expense of the public register and the Haifa taxpayer and is a criminal offense."
Sophie asked the city councilwoman in her response: "The reviewer's report and the committee's recommendations speak for themselves."
The response of attorney Sarit Golan, a member of the Haifa City Council: The testimonies and hard findings emerging from the report require the opening of a criminal investigation against all those involved in the operation of the investigative review consultant to carry out investigations, which are doubtful as to some of which are permitted by law in the manner in which they were carried out and in particular the investigations relating to the council member from the opposition to the mayor and former senior employees."
Lior Detz's response from Gatekeepers: "It seems that all the red lines that a public authority sends investigators are being crossed in order to gather information against lawyers representing an association that exposes corruption and while the association is conducting public proceedings against the Haifa municipality management."
The City of Haifa did not give a response.
Accountant Yehuda Barlev's office is not interested in commenting.
Gantz revealed that "Iran and Hezbollah worked together to harm UNIFIL operations in Lebanon"
The Minister of Defense participated in the International Cyber Conference at Tel Aviv University, claiming that "Israel knows the cyber systems of its adversaries and their modes of operation"
Gantz referred, among other things, to Al-Sayyid's documentation of Hamas captivity: "a video aimed at extortion - on the back of a humanitarian issue"
8200 Unit's deputy commander revealed: "We thwarted the attempt to poison the water systems"
Defense Minister Benny Gantz spoke this morning (Wednesday) at the International Cyber Conference of the Cyber Center at Tel Aviv University where he revealed a joint attack by Iran and Hezbollah in order to harm UNIFIL forces in Lebanon, "another blow by Iran and Hezbollah to the citizens of Lebanon and the stability of the country," Gantz said.
Gantz referred, among other things, to the documentation of Hisham al-Sayyid, who was captured by Hamas in Gaza, which the military wing of the terrorist organization released: "Yesterday a video was posted aimed at extortion – on the back of a humanitarian issue.
Hamas holds the four boys captive against international law, against morality.
Hamas is responsible for this and our expectation from the international community is to act against this criminal conduct of Hamas."
He added that "the State of Israel is acting through a variety of means, and continues to turn every stone in order to bring the boys home.
As we have said before – this is a humanitarian issue, as we see it, and on this basis we will continue to act.
Blackmail attempts and mind exercises will not affect our position and conduct."
Later on, he revealed joint Iranian and Hezbollah activities: "Iran is also operating its proxies in the cyber dimension: I can reveal today, which recently detected Iranian security forces' activity in cooperation with Hezbollah, in order to harm UNIFIL forces' activities in Lebanon.
This was done by implementing a cyber operation aimed at stealing materials on UNIFIL deployment in the region, and using them by Hezbollah.
This is another blow by Iran and Hezbollah to the citizens of Lebanon, and to Lebanon's stability."
"Israel knows the cyber systems of its adversaries and their modes of operation.
We have seen in recent years the phenomenon of Iranian hacker groups operating against Israel and other countries," Gantz continued.
"The 'New Messengers' are terrorists with a keyboard who are condemned like other terrorist organizations' fighters.
We know who they are, we hurt them and their senders, and even today they are in our sights – and not just in the cyber dimension.
No attack against the citizens of Israel will be put on the agenda.
And the responsibility lies with the attackers and the country that funds and sends them.
Cyberattacks can be responded to in a variety of ways in cyberspace and in other areas."
Gantz continued the attack on the nuclear power: "Iran is leading cyber terrorism - and is making moves aimed at influencing democratic processes and administrations, as has happened in the United States presidential election and other attempts Israel is aware of.
Actions such as that of the Shahid Kawah unit, which collected information about ships, gas stations and industrial plants in several countries, were carried out under a direct directive by the Iranian leadership and the Revolutionary Guards as revealed in the investigations."
He added that "in recent years we have stopped many attempts to break into private and public companies, in Israel and abroad.
I also call on the public to demand a ‘cybernetic responsibility,' and to punish companies and bodies that do not follow the guidelines."
Gantz went on to mark Israel's next goals in the face of threats: "Our top mission, in the military, in the industries and in the various security organizations, is to build the people, train them, and leave them.
Me and the Chief of Staff placed this issue as one of the central tasks in the relevant units.
We examine the power building all the time – both in the scope of personnel, both in the subject of training and in the subject of tasks.
In the coming years, we will also need to examine the form of organization, management and operation of cyber warfare, its offensive and defensive characteristics in the IDF and the entire security system."
Finally, the defense minister concluded, calling for cooperation with the world: "There is great importance to our cooperation with the world vis--vis Iran in the cyber dimension as well.
"The same cooperation we are building in the region vis--vis Iran in terms of defense vis--vis various threats - we are expanding in the cyber dimension as well."
The deputy commander of Unit 8200 revealed: "We thwarted the attempt to poison the water systems."
Uri, the deputy commander of Unit 8200, said in the unit's first public appearance at such conferences, revealing that Israel had foiled an attack on the water systems.
"Cyber threat prevention is a key part of our operations.
Our goal is to achieve superiority over the attacker, to be able to identify him and act to negate his abilities," said Lt. Commander 8200, adding "so we sometimes also find victims outside of Israel and then we contact other agencies if necessary.
We do this both independently and through collaboration with industry and other agencies, through the application and use of the tools we have developed.
8200 will not rest until the threat is removed."
As stated above, a threat was exposed to Israel's water systems and attempts to poison Israel's citizens: "We thwarted the attempt to take over Israel's critical water systems and poison them several years ago.
In another case, we also identified that a certain opponent attacked Israel and in the process, we identified that the same attacker also tried to target power plants in the United States.
This was the first indication of this attack.
This threat we were able to prevent through close cooperation with our American partners."
Watch: This is how police prepare to eliminate terrorists in civilian population
The Jerusalem Border Police are inaugurating a new "Asaf" facility that simulates shooting at a crowded crowd in response to the sequence of attacks that have taken place in recent months
Border Patrol's terror-fighting guide envelops Jerusalem: "The development, provides a relevant response to the threats of attribution and simulates the reality on the ground"
A peek into the Asaf facility
Preparing for the next attack: a string of terrorist attacks carried out in the spring by Palestinians and Israeli Arabs, during which 19 people were murdered and about 70 civilians were injured, led the Border Patrol to develop a unique technique that trains fighters to storm terrorists within a civilian population and carry out shootings in the movement.
Exposing "Israel Hayom": A glimpse into the "Asaf" facility
Popular terrorism focuses on harming civilians and aims to undermine the sense of security necessary to lead a normal life of a civilian population.
The wave of violent attacks that took place this year, with attacks in Beersheba, Hadera, Bnei Brak, Ariel, Elad, and especially the one that took place in early April on the busy Dizengoff Street in the heart of Tel Aviv, by a terrorist who was assimilated into a crowd, led the police to creative thinking for the purpose of developing a tool that could be used to train fighters to storm terrorists within a civilian population.
The work of thinking was led by the Police and Border Patrol Training Wing.
These came out in competition in the various police districts under the title "Learning Leading Commanders", in which each district was required to develop measures to help improve the policing and fighting skills of the fighters, police officers and commanders.
In the framework of the competition, and in response to the need to train Border Police fighters to combat the practice of firing in traffic and in these types of scenarios, Asaf Ben David, a terrorist combat instructor for the Jerusalem Border Patrol, developed the Asaf facility, consisting of a dynamic target, which is attached to a telescopic pole on which consists of a carrier that can be harnessed to the guide.
Their servant who guides the carrier to our death, he can practice the warrior who stands before him by controlling and moving the target to different sides and ranges.
It should be emphasized that in recent years, Border Patrol fighters and fighters have faced many attacks including the bomber, carrying out shootings and threatening while moving in arenas saturated with innocent civilians.
The Assaf facility, in its current version, is based on components and parts that are used in various fields.
For example, the upgraded and integrated telescopic rod at the facility was taken from the area of maintenance and cleanliness.
Through the facility it is possible to simulate firing in traffic within a civilian population towards a dynamic target while maintaining eye contact with the object, handling the movement brake, choosing a path forward making selective firing including practice of preventing harm to the uninvolved.
Maj. Gen. Asaf Ben David, whose facility is named after him, says: "The facility we have developed, is a breakthrough in learning and training fighters and police officers.
The development, provides a relevant response to the threats of attribution and simulates reality on the ground.
The benefit of development against the relatively cheap cost of production is a significant advantage for us in competition."
State Comptroller Warns: "Central Election Commission Not Prepared for Cyber Threats"
Netanyahu Engelman Warns International Cyber Week Against Israel's Unwillingness to Bombardment Attacks
"World War III will be a hacker war but the world is not prepared for it."
State Comptroller Matanyahu Engelman participated today (Wednesday) in the annual cyber conference of Tel Aviv University and expressed concern about cyber attacks on Israel.
"We are exposed.
Our data is visible to too many people.
Our money is exposed, our children are exposed, our health is exposed, our security is exposed.
World War III will be a cyber war, but the world is not ready for it."
Engelman said that in the framework of the cyber audits that his office is conducting, significant deficiencies were found: "In the past year we have carried out penetration checks at the Traffic Management Center in Jerusalem, in hospitals and in the tax authority systems.
In the reviews we found significant deficiencies, including the fact that very few penetration tests were carried out by public bodies and some only conducted penetration tests during the audit.
In addition, there have been deficiencies in the preparedness of the Central Election Commission for Cyber Threats."
"We at the State Comptroller's Office are committed to continuing to address this significant issue more fully, for the benefit of the citizens of Israel and the entire world," he concluded.
