Study states: Zoom meetings hurt creativity
Around 2,100 engineers and academics around the world have been asked to develop solutions to the problem – some in video sessions, some in face-to-face meetings.
The result: a virtual meeting impairs creativity and thinking outside the box
Research leader at Columbia University: "Visual focus on screen impairs idea-making process"
Fortha consolation: There is no harm to labor productivity or critical thinking.
A major scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of video programs on participants' creativity, compared to face-to-face sessions.
Unfortunately, it has been found that creativity is indeed compromised in virtual sessions through screens.
The research questionled by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia Universitywas whether remote computer-assisted meetings preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of distance.
The study itself began as early as 2016 but received a major boost in the two-year coronavirus, during which many employees moved to work from home.
"People in a personal meeting move around the room, use objects and use them for creative thinking," Brooks says.
"In a computer session, however, the concentration in maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of the creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which hampers the process of creating broad and expansive ideas."
Space is shrinking.
To test the results of the experiment and see if they will be repeated, they were tested twiceonce at Columbia University and once again in real lifeon engineers who knew each other from early acquaintances.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts – one being asked to meet in person and develop solutions to the problem, and the other being asked to do so through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to share in a similar way and solve a new problem presented to them.
In both cases, there was a decline in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking among those who met virtually on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher on ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, in the context of a thought activity, people often look at their surroundings in order to be assisted in creating ideas, while in the video session the thinking converges to the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity.
"When the people in the same room they look around and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can inspire new associations.
On the other hand, research shows that computer-based relationships change our attention so that we are more focused on the inside and the screen, and this way reduces innovation and idea creation through looking at the environment and thinking out."
There is no harm to critical thinking.
However, and before managers run employees back to the offices, the researchers note that "working through a computer did not harm productivity itself nor the people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea out of a set of ideas.
That is, the harm is focused on creativity only and not on the other forms of working with a computer."
Professor Alan Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also disapproves of the findings.
"There is a difference between mere creativity, like new uses for Frisbee (one of the research questions; EEG) and solutions of work.
It is also possible that when employees are more relaxed after an introduction, or they work from home, creativity will improve."
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also proposed future research in which such meetings would be discontinued for thinking situations and roaming the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
Dr. Olson also suggested that, following the study, only staff brainstorming sessions be resumed and, as a rule, he suggested not to be alarmed by one study but to carry out another investigation in the field.
"I wouldn't want workers to be forced back and not be happy is a bigger hit," he says.
Musk waits for Trump's return: 'It was wrong to block him'
Twitter's new buyer said he would reverse a decision, which led to a blockage of the former U.S. president's account.
"I think it was a mistake," he admitted.
Tesla and SpaceX owner Elon Musk, who recently acquired Twitter in a $44 billion deal, said Tuesday that he intended to put Trump back on the social network, which blocked him while he was president, after rioting by his supporters on Capital Hill after losing the election against Democratic candidate Joe Biden.
"I do think it was wrong to arrest Donald Trump.
I think it was a mistake," he said.
"If there are incorrect and bad tweets, they should be deleted or rendered invisible, and suspension - a temporary suspension - is appropriate, but not a permanent ban," Musk said.
By 2050, the world will lose 80% of the water available to agriculture.
A new global study predicts a significant decline over the next 25 years
Solution: Proper management of water reservoirs
A recent disturbing new study published in Earth's Future predicts that by 2050 the amount of water available to agriculture will decrease by about 80% if the rate of water consumption and growth of the world's population remain in their current usage trends.
In a study involving scientists from all the world's science agencies, scientists summarized the total amount of rainwater, rivers, and freshwater sources in the world and compared it to humanity's need for agriculture.
The conclusions of the grim study show that as of now the rate of water consumption has been doubling over and over the past 10 years, while at the same time global warming is causing the amount of rainfall in agricultural areas around the world to decrease.
According to the study's data, 84% of the world's agricultural land will experience a severe shortage of rainwater.
One of the key conclusions from the study calls on farmers around the world to adapt agriculture to climate change and the seasons, and to switch to cultivation methods that will make it easier for water to penetrate the soil in order to prevent the process of water evaporation leading to widespread waste of rainwater.
The researchers also recommend that farmers working near saltwater sources use rainwater collection technologies to prevent their flow to the sea.
Information about many students from Bar Ilan University leaked to the network
Hackers who attacked Bar Ilan University's database a few weeks ago threatened to publish the information about the students if they did not receive a financial ransom
The threat was realized and the information was posted across the network.
Students at Bar Ilan University are under attack from hackers when their personal information was posted across the network by a network attacker known as Darkrypt and who posted a ransom demand from university personnel a few weeks ago and threatened that if he was not paid an uncertain amount of money, he would publish the information under his control.
Estimates of the amount of money demanded by the attacker are that it was an amount that began with thousands of dollars and as the clock was ticking, it rose and before the information was published it had already reached several million dollars.
Facebook groups of university students and faculty are filled with angry messages and the mess is celebrated there, with students failing to access their personal information systems and unable to perform routine student assignments.
The university sent an e-mail announcing the attack had been carried out by the academic institution and that they were acting intensively to minimize the damage, while detailing some of the information leaked to the network.
No special instructions were given to those whose information had been compromised and it was said there that the university had carried out a series of actions to strengthen the security measures of the university's servers.
Line up for 40 settlements: The optical fiber reaches Binyamin
The trend of networking the periphery on a fast-paced Internet continues and now the optical fiber reaches the Binyamin Council which includes 40 settlements
The project in conjunction with the Council and telecommunications companies Telran, X-Fiber and Internet Rimon will be launched immediately after the holidays.
The Binyamin Council signed a wide-ranging agreement over the weekend to lay fiber optics in all council settlements.
The agreement with the Net-Fiber initiative in cooperation with Internet Rimon, Telleran and X-Fiber was signed after the conclusion of a large tender for which the council had been working in recent months.
The works will begin after the holidays and residents from 40 council settlements who would be interested in connecting to the fiber optic infrastructure will enjoy high speeds of up to 1 gigabyte as well as advanced end-to-house equipment that will allow for strong WiFi reception, as required at these times.
The entrants will be able to choose between high-speed internet over fiber optics or online filtered fast over fiber optics which they will provide online with a grenade.
The Council has made sure that the market remains open to competition in any situation.
The head of the Binyamin Regional Council, Israel Gantz: "These are real Zionism.
It's big news for the residents.
The experience of living in Benyamin will improve, students will be able to learn remotely if necessary, it will be possible to work from home and establish advanced businesses in communities that will receive quality internet and without delays.
I want to wish success to the expensive companies in the performing tasks in the settlements.
The people are waiting for you."
Gantz added: "Soon we will have the proper conditions for faster internet than some of the best in Israel.
We have labored for many months to bring about a foundation for the installation of fiber and now the vision becomes a reality.
I thank the media minister Jooz Handel who started the project with us already in his previous term and we are now reaping the fruits of the toil, the media minister's staff, the council members who were loyal to the details of the center and the CEOs of the companies who won the center for professional quality among the best in Israel."
Internet Rimon CEO Yariv Parr: "I thank Council Chief Yisrael Gantz and his staff for immediately lifting the glove in order to bring in a line to the thousands of council residents who will switch to fast internet use that will upgrade the quality of life in the areas of education, economics and of course leisure."
Telran Communications Group CEO Shai Aslan said: "We are pleased with the Binyamin Council's decision to connect to fast and powerful Internet infrastructure and I am confident that thanks to the group's extensive experience we will be able to give residents a fast internet just like in the center of the country."
CEO of X-Fiber, Israel Elitzur: "The establishment of communication infrastructure in Binyamin is the Zionism of 2021, X-Fiber is proud to take part in the establishment of the new infrastructure in the biblical areas of Binyamin, I have no doubt that thanks to our familiarity with Judea and Samaria in general and Binyamin in particular, we will meet every engineering challenge in order to bring the high-speed Internet to every home throughout the council."
We checked: What do the side effects after the coronavirus vaccine say?
Many people who are vaccinated feel weak, warm, and tired after receiving the injection, while others feel nothing
Can it indicate a stronger immune system of those who do experience these phenomena, or is it a baseless rumor?
As more and more people become vaccinated, the lack of information about the side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are untrue.
Is the immune system of those who have developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies have responded less severely to the vaccine, which may prove that their system is unable to fight off a foreign body that enters the body?
"There are several levels of responses to the vaccine," says Dr. David Dvir, head of the Unitarian Primary Medicine Division and a member of the IDF Advisory Committee (Team for the Treatment of Pestilence), reassuring: "Headaches, fatigue, pains in place, these are the immediate responses of the immune system.
This is how the body reacts to the entry of a foreign body into the system."
Is there a link between the levels of antibodies that develop to the side effects?
"There is no correlation between the sensations and the development of antibodies against the virus.
About 60%-50% feel the side effects, but about 90% develop protection against the virus.
It was not found that people who developed stronger responses were more protected."
"In medical literature, there is no correlation between an immediate response to the level of the vaccine.
In some trials where people also received placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
It is also a mental component - how the person perceives the vaccine, if he expects there to be side effects.
Many of the phenomena that happen could also happen normally, but since the public has been vaccinated it attributes the response to the vaccine itself, and this is a bias that is seen regarding vaccines in general – attribution of phenomena that happen near the vaccine and are attributed to it."
According to Dr. Dvir, the causes of the reported common phenomena, such as weakness and headaches, are not yet known.
Regarding myocarditis, opinions are divided.
"There are all kinds of theories on the subject, but it should be noted that the virus itself causes higher rates of myocarditis than the vaccine.
One theory is that this is a strong immune response."
Is it even possible to assess the strength of a immune system?
"When students were exposed to the flu virus, they showed that those who did not sleep or were under higher pressure were more susceptible to infection.
Besides, there are laboratory parameters that check the immune system or its components.
When there is a decrease in the immune system, it is immediately seen.
People get a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It's not like anyone's walking around with a weak immune system and unaware of it.
These are people who come to clarification because of repeated events of infectious diseases, and what affects the system are banal things: stress, nutrition, sleep.
By the way, we also don't want a very strong immune system, because it can cause autoimmune diseases."
Soon, mRNA vaccines will appear in more contexts, thanks to the great knowledge that has accumulated about them in recent times.
"There is no doubt that Yasla opened up to other vaccines of this kind.
This technology is being tested for many uses beyond vaccines – for oncological diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the substance remains very little time in the body - goes in, does its operation, and then breaks down.
This technology is not new, but it has received a serious boost due to the very great need for rapid vaccination.
Now, for example, we know that the three-week interval between doses is too small, and some vaccine experts claim that after a third dose we may not need another vaccine in the near term, so it is unclear whether we are going to be in a vaccine state every six months or whether the third dose will give a greater margin."
Thousands injured: Severe privacy default on Route 6
Route 6 customers?
Your private information, including full name, addresses, payment amounts and full travel details, may have been disclosed
According to the Privacy Protection Authority, Derech Eretz company violated the Privacy Protection Act and its regulations.
After a report by Derech Eretz, the operator of Route 6 in Israel, about a security incident that took place in the company, the Privacy Protection Authority began an enforcement process.
As part of the incident, security weaknesses were discovered on its payment website, which allowed the exposure of a lot of information from the invoices of the member's customers, which were exposed to all.
Among other things, customers' invoices were exposed over a short period of time and these invoices included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, vehicle location, travel dates, and at what hours.
Furthermore, because the Derech Eretz company did not legally document access to its systems, it is not possible to know accurately for what period of time unauthorized parties could access the company's systems.
In the breach letter, passed by the Privacy Protection Authority to the company, the Authority emphasized that most of the large companies and organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that with the development of threats and risks, the organization is obligated to scrutinize the risks being updated and to act in accordance with the updated security measures accepted in the circumstances of the case, in accordance with the nature and nature of the database.
As a result, companies and organizations have a duty to update their systems and conduct risk surveys and penetration tests, in order to examine the changing risks and prepare for them.
It is also mandatory for companies and organizations to use an automated documentation mechanism and employee training should be conducted, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy Protection (Information Security) Regulations.
In accordance with the findings of the oversight, the Authority determined that the company had violated the provisions of the Privacy Protection Act and its regulations as well as required the company to perform several corrective actions.
Route 6 operator said: "The issue has been handled in accordance with the most stringent requirements"
Travel warning to Istanbul: Surprising news for Israelis from Turkish airlines
Turkish Airlines and Pegasus will allow Israelis to change their destination or flight date
In a message to Israelis who booked tickets to Turkey before the travel warning: The airlines will allow the flight dates to be changed.
Reminder: Earlier this week the Counterterrorism Bureau raised the severity of the travel warning to Istanbul to a level four.
This is the highest level and means "high threat level: do not arrive in this country and in the event of a stay you must leave the country as soon as possible".
Turkish Airlines and Pegasus said they would allow Israelis who booked their flight before the departure of the travel warning, i.e. before the date 13.6.22, to replace their destination or flight date.
This is in an appeal to the airline.
Tourism Minister Rezbozov said: "The citizens of Israel should not pay an economic price because of terrorist threats.
I am pleased that large airlines like Turkish Airlines and Pegasus have complied with our request and I hope that additional companies will respond similarly to all Israeli citizens who cancelled their holiday in Turkey because of the severe travel warning."
